\begin_body

\begin_layout Section
Model
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Model"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section presents a Schumpeterian model based on 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "abramsPatentValueCitations2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, featuring growth through creative destruction by entrants, as well as
 the possibility for incumbent monopolist of researching a defensive technology
 that increases research costs for entrants.
 I first present a single-sector model to clarify the mechanism at play
 within each sector in the economy and study the properties of a constant-growth
 equilibrium analytically.
 I derive sufficient conditions under which markup increases lower R&D productiv
ity, and show that this occur only if the distribution of inventors shifts
 in favor of incumbent firms carrying out defensive innovation.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the empirical analysis, I used the HHI as a measure of concentration
 and market power.
 Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:Using-the-Lerner"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows that the Lerner Index from NBER-CES, a standard measure of markups,
 is strongly correlated with the HHI in my sample, justifying the reduced-form
 mapping I adopt in this section.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 I also show that in this model, when the supply of inventors is rigid,
 inventors' productivity is unaffected by markup changes.
 Then, I move to consider a two-sector model, where each sector is identical
 to the single-sector model, and the supply of inventors is perfectly rigid,
 which shuts down within-sector misallocation occurring independently of
 inventors' movements across sectors.
 I show that increasing markups in one of the two sectors of the economy
 lead to a misallocation of R&D resources towards defensive innovation in
 the less competitive sector.
 Finally, I study the optimal allocation of R&D subsidies needed to achieve
 maximum growth in a calibration of the two-sector model that matches moments
 of the R&D distribution in 1997, the starting year for my empirical analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All omitted proofs are reported in Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app: Omitted-Proofs"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Single-sector Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Preferences and production
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Preferences-and-production"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the following continuous time economy with a single final good.
 There is a representative household with King-Plosser-Rebelo preferences
 over consumption and R&D labor 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbb{E}_{t}\int_{t}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho\left(s-t\right)\right)\left(\ln C_{s}-\frac{\chi\left(L_{s}^{RD}\right)^{1+\frac{1}{\phi}}}{1+\frac{1}{\phi}}\right)\mathrm{d}s,\label{eq:Utility}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is the Frisch labor supply.
 In addition, the representative household inelastically supplies 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 units of production labor.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
While this assumption is not necessary for the results to hold, it simplifies
 the analysis considerably.
 In the following section, I will consider both production and research
 labor as given by a fixed endowment in the constant growth equilibrium
 of the economy.
 In that case, the assumption is equivalent to assuming that both labor
 endowments grow at a constant rate.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The representative household owns a differentiated portfolio of all the
 firms in the economy, with rate of return 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}$
\end_inset

, and receives a wages 
\begin_inset Formula $w,w^{RD},$
\end_inset

 for each unit of production and research labor, respectively.
 I assume that the economy is closed and that the final good is only used
 for consumption, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}=Y_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The above utility function yields the Euler equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\dot{C_{t}}}{C_{t}}=r_{t}-\rho.
\]

\end_inset

It also yields the R&D labor supply
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{t}^{RD}=\left(\frac{w_{t}^{RD}}{\chi C_{t}}\right)^{\phi}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumption good in the economy in each instant is a Cobb-Douglas aggregate
 of a measure-one continuum of products
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln Y_{t}=\int_{0}^{1}\ln y_{t}(i)\mathrm{d}i.\label{eq:Y}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The consumption good in the economy is taken as the numeraire.
 The market for each product 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}(i)$
\end_inset

 consists of an incumbent and a fringe of competitors.
 In what follows, I focus on a single market, dropping the argument 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Each agent 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 in the sector has the linear production technology:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{j,t}=c_{j,t}l_{j,t},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j,t}$
\end_inset

 denotes the labor requirement for agent 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 to produce a unit of output, and 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{j,t}$
\end_inset

 denotes the production labor employed by the firm.
 The incumbent and competitors produce undifferentiated goods, and differ
 in their labor requirement.
 Competitors have labor requirement 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{e,t}=c_{t}$
\end_inset

, while the incumbent faces a lower unit labor requirement 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{I,t}=\frac{c_{t}}{\phi}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi>1$
\end_inset

.
 The incumbent maximizes profits by choosing a price 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{t}$
\end_inset

 for her product.
 Profit maximization gives an optimum limit price 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{t}=w_{t}c_{t}$
\end_inset

, which leads her to capture the entire market and realize profits
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pi_{t}=\left(c_{e,t}-c_{I,t}\right)w_{t}y_{t}=\left(\frac{\phi-1}{\phi}\right)c_{t}w_{t}y_{t}.
\]

\end_inset

Therefore, the incumbent acts as a monopolist, charging a markup 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi>1$
\end_inset

 on its marginal cost.
 By the Cobb-Douglas assumption on the final good, the demand facing each
 product line is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{t}=\frac{Y_{t}}{p_{t}}=\frac{Y_{t}}{w_{t}c_{t}}.
\]

\end_inset

Therefore, equilibrium normalized profits read
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\Pi_{t}}{Y_{t}}\equiv\pi=\left(\frac{\phi-1}{\phi}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Innovation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both incumbents and entrants can conduct innovation activity that, if successful
, reduces their unit costs to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{I,t+\Delta_{t}}=\frac{c_{e,t}}{\left(1+\eta\right)\phi},\quad\eta>1
\]

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 parametrizes the percentage increase in productivity for the innovating
 firm, relative to the technology previously operated by the incumbent.
 I assume spillovers from realized innovations as follows.
 Whenever either the incumbent or an entrant realize an innovation, all
 other firms gain access to a technology with unit costs
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{e,t+\Delta_{t}}=\frac{c_{e,t}}{\left(1+\eta\right)}.
\]

\end_inset

These assumptions imply that, if entrants realize an innovation, they outcompete
 previous incumbents and become the new monopolists.
 Displaced incumbents join the pool of entrants and from instant 
\begin_inset Formula $t+\Delta t$
\end_inset

 onwards operate the technology 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $c_{e,t+\Delta_{t}}$
\end_inset

.
 This amounts to assuming that the incumbent's technology becomes obsolete
 after displacement.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
An alternative interpretation of this assumption is that incumbents are
 forced to scrap the assets needed to operate the innovative technology
 upon destruction, so that the technology is no longer available to them
 onwards.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Technically, this innovation structure removes the need to keep track of
 the number of realized innovations.
 Indeed, in each product market the relative productivity of incumbents
 relative to entrants is fixed at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, making it possible to formulate the choice of innovation as a recursive
 problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Incumbents' and entrants' innovation differ in two respects.
 First, successful incumbents' R&D produces a 
\emph on
patent wall 
\emph default
of size 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega>1$
\end_inset

, which decreases the success probability of entrants' innovations.
 Second, successful entrants' R&D results in an implemented innovation with
 certainty, while incumbents adopt new technologies with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in[0,1].$
\end_inset

 This parameter can be interpreted in two ways.
 The first interpretation is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 captures the probability that the newly discovered technology is compatible
 with the incumbents' current production techniques.
 The second interpretation is related to the radical nature of incumbents'
 innovations.
 A low value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 reduces the expected productivity improvement from an innovation by the
 incumbent.
 In other words, the lower 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda,$
\end_inset

 the more incremental are incumbents' innovations.
 Under these assumptions, incumbents 
\emph on
always
\emph default
 obtain a patent wall, but they only implement their innovations with probabilit
y 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This specification connects to the empirical evidence in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "argentePatentsProductsProduct2020a"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, who show that large incumbent firms tend to produce many patents, but
 implement a small number of product innovations.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "acemogluIntellectualPropertyRights2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, I assume that innovation investments consist in the choice of an arrival
 rate of new discoveries 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{I}$
\end_inset

, and that R&D costs are increasing and convex in this arrival rate.
 I specify incumbents' R&D costs as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C\left(x_{I};w^{RD}\right)=\alpha_{I}\frac{x_{I}^{\gamma}}{\gamma}w^{RD},\ \gamma>1,
\]

\end_inset

where the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{I}\frac{x_{I}^{\gamma}}{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 indicates the amount of inventors that the incumbent needs to obtain innovation
s with a flow probability 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{I}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{RD}$
\end_inset

 is the wage paid to inventors.
 For simplicity, I assume that incumbents can only have one available innovation
 at a time.
 That is, incumbents can only erect 
\emph on
one
\emph default
 patent wall of size 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega>1$
\end_inset

, and cannot invest in further innovation until this wall is destroyed at
 a rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

, which captures the pace of patent expiration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under these assumptions, incumbents' values at any given instant are just
 a function of the state of the patent wall in the product market they operate,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\in\left\{ 1,\omega\right\} .$
\end_inset

 Given the recursive nature of the problem, I drop time indexes in what
 follows.
 Incumbents' value functions read:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
rV(1)-\dot{V}(1) & =\max_{x_{I}}\left\{ \left(\frac{\phi-1}{\phi}\right)Y-\alpha_{I}\frac{x_{I}^{\gamma}}{\gamma}w^{RD}+x_{I}\left(V(\omega)-V(1)\right)-x_{e,1}V(1)\right\} ,\label{eq:v_1}\\
rV(\omega)-\dot{V}(\omega) & =\left(\frac{\phi-1}{\phi}\right)Y+\delta\left(V(1)-V(\omega)\right)-x_{e,\omega}V(\omega),\label{eq:v_om}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{e,1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{e,\omega}$
\end_inset

 denote entrants' innovation intensities, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the interest rate in the economy to be determined in equilibrium, and
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 the rate of patent expiration.
 The first line displays the flow value to incumbents that operate in a
 market not protected by a patent wall.
 There, incumbents realize instantaneous profits 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{\phi-1}{\phi}\right)Y$
\end_inset

,
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 and choose their innovation intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{I}$
\end_inset

, taking the researchers' wage 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{RD}$
\end_inset

 and the entrants' innovation intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{e,1}$
\end_inset

 as given.
 If entrants are successful at rate 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{e,1}$
\end_inset

, incumbents are destroyed.
 If incumbents' innovation is successful at rate 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{I}$
\end_inset

, they obtain the patent wall 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

, which grants them the protected value 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\omega)$
\end_inset

.
 When a patent wall is in place, incumbents realize the same flow of profits
 as in the unprotected state, since economy-wide spillovers imply that incumbent
s are unable to reap profits from implemented innovations.
 However, incumbents face a different entrants' innovation intensity, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{e,\omega}$
\end_inset

, which is lower than 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{e,1}$
\end_inset

 due to the patent wall in place, as I will show below.
 Finally, incumbents in state 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 face a flow probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 that the patent wall is exogenously destroyed, in which case they transition
 back to the unprotected state.
 Under these assumptions, the optimal incumbent's R&D decision is given
 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x_{I}=\bm{1}\left\{ V(\omega)-V(1)>0\right\} \left(\frac{V(\omega)-V(1)}{\alpha_{I}w^{RD}}\right)^{\frac{1}{\gamma-1}}.\label{eq:RD_I}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "abramsPatentValueCitations2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, I assume that each market has a mass of atomistic entrants, indexed by
 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, who face innovation costs that feature congestion externalities
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C\left(x_{e,\Omega,j};w^{RD}\right)=\zeta\Omega x_{e,\Omega,j}x_{e,\Omega}w^{RD}.
\]

\end_inset

In this specification, 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

 parametrizes the inventor requirement to obtain a unit aggregate entrants'
 innovation rate when the market is not protected by patent walls, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=1$
\end_inset

.
 Individuals costs are linear in the total entrants' research intensity
 in the product market, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{e,\Omega}\equiv\int_{\mathcal{J}}x_{e,\Omega,j}\mathrm{d}j.$
\end_inset

 In other terms, individual entry costs increase with the aggregate entry
 rate.
 Successful entrants obtain a new unprotected technology, regardless of
 the state of the market that they target, based on the assumption that
 they do not rely on patents from previous incumbents.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under the above assumptions, the free entry condition for entrants targeting
 a market with patent wall 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 reads
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\max_{x_{e,\Omega,i}}\left\{ x_{e,\Omega,i}V(1)-\zeta\Omega x_{e,\Omega,i}x_{e,\Omega}w^{RD}\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

This condition pins down the entry rate for each product market with patent
 wall 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x_{e,\Omega}=\frac{V(1)}{\zeta\Omega w^{RD}},\quad\Omega\in\{1,\omega\}.\label{eq:RD_e}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This expression clarifies the effect of defensive innovation in this model.
 The size of the patent wall 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 represents the factor decrease in the entry rate when a defensive innovation
 is successful.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Equilibrium with Constant Growth
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The laws of motion of product markets across protected and unprotected states
 is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\dot{\mu}_{1} & =-\left(x_{I}+x_{e,1}\right)\mu_{1}+\delta\mu_{\omega}+x_{e,\omega}\mu_{e,\omega}+x_{e,1}\mu_{e,1},\label{eq: dist1-1}\\
\dot{\mu}_{\omega} & =-\left(x_{e,\omega}+\delta\right)\mu_{\omega}+x_{I}\mu_{1},\label{eq: dist2-1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{e,\omega}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{e,1}$
\end_inset

 denote the mass of entrants targeting protected and unprotected markets,
 respectively.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: dist1-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 states that the mass of unprotected products decreases when incumbents
 successfully develop an innovation at flow probability, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{I},$
\end_inset

 or entrants displace existing incumbents at rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{e,1}$
\end_inset

.
 Products instead become unprotected if existing patent walls depreciate,
 or successful entrants become new monopolists.
 Conversely, Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: dist1-2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows that protected markets loose mass whenever entrants displace existing
 protected incumbents or defensive patents depreciate, and gain mass when
 incumbents in unprotected markets develop defensive innovations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mass of entrants in the two types of product markets is determined in
 equilibrium following the laws of motion:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\dot{\mu}_{e,1} & =-\left(x_{e,1}+x_{I}\right)\mu_{e,1}+x_{e,1}\mu_{1}+\delta\mu_{e,\omega},\label{eq: dist3-1}\\
\dot{\mu}_{e,\omega} & =-\left(x_{e,\omega}+\delta\right)\mu_{e,\omega}+x_{e,\omega}\mu_{\omega}+x_{I}\mu_{e,1}.\label{eq: dist4-1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Here, the first line states that the pool of entrants in unprotected markets
 contracts if entrants develop innovations at rate 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{e,1},$
\end_inset

 or incumbents make markets protected at rate 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{I}.$
\end_inset

 The pool of entrants in markets with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=1$
\end_inset

 instead grows when incumbents get displaced by successful entrants and
 rejoin the ranks of outsiders, or previously protected markets loose their
 defensive walls.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: dist4-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is obtained analogously.
 Given research intensities, clearing in the labor markets for production
 and research labor require:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
L & =\int_{0}^{1}l(i)\mathrm{d}i,\label{eq: Lprod}\\
L^{RD} & =\zeta\left(\omega x_{e,\omega}\mu_{e,\omega}+x_{e,1}\mu_{e,1}\right)+\alpha_{I}\frac{x_{I}^{\gamma}}{\gamma}\mu_{1}.\label{eq: LRD}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A constant growth equilibrium of this economy is defined as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Constant Growth Equilibrium
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A constant growth equilibrium is a sequence of values 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ V_{t}(1),V_{t}(\omega)\right\} ,$
\end_inset

 production workers' and inventors' wage sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ w_{t}^{RD},w_{t}\right\} $
\end_inset

, and incumbents' and entrants' R&D decisions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{I,t},x_{e,1,t},x_{e,\omega,t}\right\} $
\end_inset

 such that, given an endowment of production labor, 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{RD}$
\end_inset

: (i) incumbents maximize values 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:v_1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:v_om"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, taking entrants R&D decisions as given; (ii) entrants' R&D decisions satisfy
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RD_I"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RD_e"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 taking 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{t}(1)$
\end_inset

 as given; (iii) the distribution of incumbents and entrants across protected
 and unprotected markets is constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\mu}_{1}=\dot{\mu}_{\omega}=\dot{\mu}_{e,1}=\dot{\mu}_{e,\omega}=0$
\end_inset

 in Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: dist1-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: dist4-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

; (iv) values in each instant are determined by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:v_1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:v_om"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

; (v) consumers maximize utility 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Utility"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, choosing consumption and R&D labor optimally; (vi) labor markets clear
 according to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: Lprod"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: LRD"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

; (vii) product markets clear, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}=Y_{t}$
\end_inset

; and (viii) aggregate output 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Y"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 grows at the constant rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $g\equiv\dot{Y}_{t}/Y_{t}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following proposition summarizes the properties of the constant growth
 equilibrium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Existence and Uniqueness of the Constant Growth Equilibrium
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:CGE"

\end_inset

For any endowments of production labor 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, there exists a unique constant growth equilibrium.
 Denoting optimal incumbents' and entrants' choices as 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{I}^{\star},x_{e,\omega}^{\star},x_{e,1}^{\star},$
\end_inset

 and the masses of incumbents and entrants across states as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{1}^{\star},\mu_{\omega}^{\star},\mu_{e,1}^{\star},\mu_{e,\omega}^{\star}$
\end_inset

, the constant growth rate of the economy is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g=\eta\left[x_{e,\omega}^{\star}\mu_{e,\omega}^{\star}+x_{e,1}^{\star}\mu_{e,1}^{\star}+\lambda x_{I}^{\star}\mu_{1}^{\star}\right],
\]

\end_inset

and inventors' productivity reads
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{g}{L^{RD}}=\eta\frac{x_{e,\omega}^{\star}\mu_{e,\omega}^{\star}+x_{e,1}^{\star}\mu_{e,1}^{\star}+\lambda x_{I}^{\star}\mu_{1}^{\star}}{\zeta\left(\omega x_{e,\omega}^{\star}\mu_{e,\omega}^{\star}+x_{e,1}^{\star}\mu_{e,1}^{\star}\right)+\alpha_{I}\frac{\left(x_{I}^{\star}\right)^{\gamma}}{\gamma}\mu_{1}^{\star}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expression for inventors' productivity can be used to obtain a first
 intuition of the mechanism through which higher markups lead to decreased
 productivity in this model.
 First, note that a unit of total entrants' research intensity in either
 protected and unprotected markets produces the same growth.
 Indeed, by the expression for growth, it is clear that a unit increase
 in either 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{e,\omega}^{\star}\mu_{e,\omega}^{\star}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{e,1}^{\star}\mu_{e,1}^{\star}$
\end_inset

 gives a growth of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

.
 However, the unit labor requirement of research intensity in protected
 markets is larger than in unprotected markets as a result of defensive
 patents.
 This is evident from the first term at the denominator, which shows that
 a unit of total research in protected markets requires 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta\omega$
\end_inset

 inventors, compared with just 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

 in unprotected markets.
 These facts immediately imply that any force that pushes entrants toward
 protected markets will lower their inventor productivity.
 One such force is an increase in incumbents' research intensity that outstrips
 entrants', which acts to increase 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{e,\omega},$
\end_inset

 the mass of entrants active in protected markets.
 As I show formally below, an increase in the markup raises the value of
 monopolistic positions, which pushes up both incumbents' and entrants'
 research intensities 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{I}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{e,\omega}.$
\end_inset

 This results in an increase in 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{e,\omega}$
\end_inset

 only if incumbents' R&D intensity is more elastic than entrants'.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
The following proposition states the main result in this section: Higher
 markups unambiguously increase research efforts by incumbents and entrants,
 as well as the share of R&D labor accruing to incumbents.
 The proposition also states the main condition for this result to lead
 to a fall in overall inventors' productivity in terms of sufficient statistics.
 In particular, the incumbents' R&D elasticity to markups must be larger
 than entrants'.
 This condition is satisfied in the data, as the estimates in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: RegStats"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 show that incumbents increase their share of inventors following increases
 in markups.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Effects of Markup Increases on Innovation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop: partialEq"

\end_inset

Suppose that defensive research is effective, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega>1$
\end_inset

.
 The constant growth equilibrium features positive incumbents' research,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{I}^{\star}>0$
\end_inset

; markup increases raise both incumbents' and entrants' research effort
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial x_{I}^{\star}}{\partial\phi}>0,\ \frac{\partial x_{e,\omega}^{\star}}{\partial\phi}>0\ \frac{\partial x_{e,1}^{\star}}{\partial\phi}>0;
\]

\end_inset

and the share of R&D labor employed by incumbents increases with markup
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\frac{L_{I}}{L^{RD}}}{\partial\phi}=\frac{\partial\left(\nicefrac{\alpha_{I}\frac{x_{I}^{\gamma}}{\gamma}\mu_{1}}{L^{RD}}\right)}{\partial\phi}>0.
\]

\end_inset

Moreover, if (i) 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

; (ii) inventor supply is not fully inelastic; and (iii) the model parameters
 are such that equilibrium incumbents' research effort is more elastic than
 entrants', 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial x_{I}^{\star}}{\partial\phi}\frac{\phi}{x_{I}^{\star}}>\frac{\partial x_{e,\omega}^{\star}}{\partial\phi}\frac{\phi}{x_{e,\omega}^{\star}},
\]

\end_inset

it further holds
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\left(\nicefrac{g}{L^{RD}}\right)}{\partial\phi}<0.
\]

\end_inset

That is, an increase in the markup, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, lowers equilibrium inventors' productivity.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
With quadratic costs and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=0,$
\end_inset

the sufficient condition: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{\frac{\phi-1}{\phi}}\left(\frac{\alpha_{I}-\zeta\omega\left(\omega-1\right)}{\alpha_{I}\zeta\omega}\right)>\rho.
\]

\end_inset

it holds:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial x_{I}^{\star}}{\partial\phi}\frac{\phi}{x_{I}^{\star}}>\frac{\partial x_{e,\omega}^{\star}}{\partial\phi}\frac{\phi}{x_{e,\omega}^{\star}},\ \text{and}\ \frac{\partial\left(\nicefrac{g}{L^{RD}}\right)}{\partial\phi}<0.
\]

\end_inset

That is, incumbents' research responds more than entrants' to markup increases,
 and an increase in the markup, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, lowers equilibrium inventors' productivity.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Moreover,Consider the above model with a perfectly elastic production and
 R&D labor supply.
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=0,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{\frac{\phi-1}{\phi}}\left(\frac{\alpha_{I}-\zeta\omega\left(\omega-1\right)}{\alpha_{I}\zeta\omega}\right)>\rho.
\]

\end_inset

 An increase in the markup factor 
\begin_inset Formula $m\equiv\frac{\phi-1}{\phi}$
\end_inset

, increases incumbents' and entrants' R&D, growth, and the incumbents' share
 of total R&D labor, and decreases inventor productivity, 
\begin_inset Formula $g/L^{RD}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The intuition behind this proposition is that higher markups raise the value
 of monopolistic positions, thus raising both entrants' and incumbents'
 research effort.
 In addition, this leads to an overall increase in inventors employed by
 incumbents.
 Importantly, this holds only if defensive R&D is effective, showing the
 importance of this channel to reproduce the empirical findings in Table
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: RegStats"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 However, this finding is not sufficient to generate a fall in inventor
 productivity.
 That is because the overall change in inventors' productivity can be decomposed
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{d}\left(\frac{g}{L^{RD}}\right) & =\mathrm{d}\left(\frac{L_{e}}{L^{RD}}P_{e}\right)+\mathrm{d}\left(\frac{L_{I}}{L^{RD}}P_{I}\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{I}$
\end_inset

 denote entrants' and incumbents' productivity, respectively.
 As long as incumbents' productivity is lower than entrants, a reallocation
 of inventors towards dominant firm leads to a decrease in inventor productivity.
 However, this effect can in principle be offset by an increase in entrants'
 productivity.
 The sufficient conditions in Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop: partialEq"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 ensure that this is not the case.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Corollary 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cor: parameters"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 in the Appendix provides parametric sufficient conditions for the case
 with quadratic costs, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=2$
\end_inset

, which is analytically tractable.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In particular, if incumbents' research effort is more elastic than entrants',
 an increase in markups reduces the overall share of unprotected markets,
 making entry overall more difficult as well as reducing entrants' productivity.
 This reasoning also clarifies why the condition is sufficient.
 Indeed, a fall in inventors' productivity occurs as long as the increase
 in creative-destruction growth by entrants is not high enough relative
 to the increase in defensive innovation by entrants.
 As noted above, this condition is satisfied in the data and always appear
 to be in numerical simulations, regardless of specific assumptions on parameter
 values.
 In particular, the assumption 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

 is not necessary to generate the result, but it gives clear analytical
 results in the proof to this proposition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to stress that the decline in productivity requires a strictly
 positive elasticity of inventors' supply.
 As I show in Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:Labor Demand"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 in the Appendix, 
\emph on
aggregate
\emph default
 inventor labor demand is increasing in markups.
 As a result, when inventors' supply is fully rigid, wage effects need to
 fully offset the increase in labor demand, and by the uniqueness of the
 CGE, the allocation of inventors across incumbents and entrants is fixed.
 Indeed, aggregate labor demand is uniquely pinned down by research intensities
 through the stationary distribution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:OneSecCS"

\end_inset

 provides a graphical illustration of the comparative statics for an increase
 in markup in a calibration of the one-sector model, which follows the strategy
 described in detail in the following section.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The parameters of the calibration are chosen to match moments of the R&D
 expenditure distribution as in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Two-sectors"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and the complete set of parameters is reported in Appendix.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An increase in the markup raises profits, thereby increasing the value
 of dominant positions and propelling both incumbents' and entrants' research.
 Importantly, the incumbents' inventor demand is more elastic to increased
 profits, which raises the overall proportion of researchers employed in
 defensive projects.
 Although overall growth increases with higher aggregate R&D, the productivity
 of inventors falls, as they are allocated to incumbents.
 Two observations are in order.
 First, with a fixed supply of inventors, equilibrium allocations do not
 change with increased profits, leaving R&D productivity unaffected.
 Second, in the absence of defensive innovation, the increase in profits
 would only result in increased entry and growth, leaving productivity constant.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the absence of defensive innovation, all firms operates in unprotected
 markets and there is no incumbent research.
 From the expression for growth in Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop: partialEq"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 inventor productivity is constant at 
\begin_inset Formula $\nicefrac{\eta}{\zeta}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In this setting, an increase in the markup factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\left(\phi-1\right)}{\phi}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Increases profits;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Increases both entrants' and incumbents' RD;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Increases the incumbents' RD share;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Increases sectoral growth;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Reduces sectoral RD productivity.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Consider the ratio:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\alpha_{I}\frac{x_{I}^{2}}{2}\mu_{1}}{\zeta\omega x_{e,\omega}\left(\mu_{e,\omega}+\mu_{e,1}\right)+\alpha_{I}\frac{x_{I}^{2}}{2}\mu_{1}} & =\\
\frac{\alpha_{I}\frac{x_{I}^{2}}{2}\mu_{1}}{\zeta\omega x_{e,\omega}\left(1+\frac{\left(\omega-1\right)x_{1}-\omega x_{e,\omega}}{\left(x_{I}+\omega x_{e,\omega}\right)}\mu_{1}\right)+\alpha_{I}\frac{x_{I}^{2}}{2}\mu_{1}} & =\\
\frac{\alpha_{I}\frac{x_{I}^{2}}{2}}{\zeta\omega x_{e,\omega}\left(\frac{\left(x_{I}+x_{e,\omega}\right)}{x_{e,\omega}}+\frac{\left(\omega-1\right)x_{1}-\omega x_{e,\omega}}{\left(x_{I}+\omega x_{e,\omega}\right)}\right)+\alpha_{I}\frac{x_{I}^{2}}{2}} & =\\
\frac{x_{I}}{\frac{2\zeta\omega}{\alpha_{I}}\frac{x_{e,\omega}}{x_{I}}\left(\frac{\left(1+\frac{x_{e,\omega}}{x_{I}}\right)}{\frac{x_{e,\omega}}{x_{I}}}+\frac{\left(\omega-1\right)-\omega\frac{x_{e,\omega}}{x_{I}}}{\left(1+\omega\frac{x_{e,\omega}}{x_{I}}\right)}\right)+x_{I}} & =\\
\frac{x_{I}}{\frac{2\zeta\omega}{\alpha_{I}}z\left(\frac{1+z}{z}+\frac{\left(\omega-1\right)-\omega z}{1+\omega z}\right)+x_{I}} & =
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now the question is: how does the denominator change with 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

?
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial\frac{z\left(\frac{1+z}{z}+\frac{\left(\omega-1\right)-\omega z}{1+\omega z}\right)}{\partial z}m & =\left(\frac{1+z}{z}+\frac{\left(\omega-1\right)-\omega z}{1+\omega z}\right)+z\left(-\frac{1}{z^{2}}+\frac{-\omega\left(1+\omega z\right)+\omega^{2}z-\omega\left(\omega-1\right)}{\left(1+\omega z\right)^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\left(1+\frac{\left(\omega-1\right)-\omega z}{1+\omega z}\right)+\omega z\left(\frac{-\omega}{\left(1+\omega z\right)^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{\omega}{1+\omega z}\right)+\left(\frac{-\omega^{2}z}{\left(1+\omega z\right)^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{\omega}{\left(1+\omega z\right)^{2}}>0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Clearly, increase in growth is a byproduct of the perfectly elastic supply
 of inventors, who get drawn into R&D by increased profits.
 It is apparent that the increased in growth is driven by the increase in
 entrants' R&D activity, while the decrease in inventor productivity is
 driven by the increase in the inventors' share hired by monopolists engaged
 in defensive innovation.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement th
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Comparative Statics for Changes in the Markup in the Single-Sector Model
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
