\begin_layout Subsection
Calibration and Policy
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Two-sectors"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, I calibrate a two-sector extension of the model presented
 in the previous Section, with two main objectives.
 First, I want to analyze misallocation 
\emph on
across 
\emph default
sectors, and show that, under a realistic calibration, this extension can
 qualitatively reproduce the main findings of the empirical analysis.
 I focus on the benchmark with
\emph on
 fixed
\emph default
 inventor supply where, as seen in the previous section, markups have no
 effect on inventors' productivity within sectors.
 This choice excludes that my findings are driven by within-sector misallocation
 alone.
 Second, I show that growth is maximized when R&D subsidies are allocated
 to entrants in the less competitive sector.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Model description
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumption good in the economy is given by the Cobb Douglas aggregate:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ln Y_{t}=\beta_{1}\ln Y_{1,t}+\beta_{2}\ln Y_{2,t},\quad\beta_{1}+\beta_{2}=1
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{1,t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{2,t}$
\end_inset

 are produced as in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Preferences-and-production"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and the markup parameter, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, is allowed to vary across the two sectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The household side of the economy is unchanged relative to the one-sector
 model.
 In this section, however, the supply of inventors is assumed to be fully
 rigid and given by 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{RD}=100.$
\end_inset

 This assumption is motivated by two considerations.
 First, a fixed inventor supply captures an aggregate scarcity of inventors,
 allowing me to focus exclusively on their allocation across sectors.
 Second, as discussed above, in this benchmark markup changes have no effect
 on misallocation if inventors are not allowed to move across sectors.
 Therefore, the results below isolate the effect of inventors' transitions
 across sectors on misallocation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the presence of two markets, labor market clearing for production
 workers and inventors is now given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
L & =\sum_{i=1}^{2}\int_{0}^{1}l_{i,j,t}\left(w^{RD}\right)\mathrm{d}j,\label{eq: Lprod-1}\\
L^{RD} & =\sum_{i=1}^{2}L_{i,t}^{RD}\left(w^{RD}\right),\label{eq: LRD-1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 denotes sectors and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 the product markets in each sector.
 I define a constant growth equilibrium as in the previous section.
 Given the Cobb-Douglas assumption on the final good, growth is now given
 by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta\ln Y_{t}=\sum_{i=1}\beta_{i}g_{i},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

 denotes the sector-specific output growth obtained as in Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop: partialEq"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app: twoSec"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 reports the derivations for the two-sector model and a complete description
 of the equations characterizing the equilibrium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Calibration
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Calibration"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I calibrate my model in order to match features of the R&D distribution
 and concentration around 1997, the starting year for my analysis.
 This approach provides conservative parameter choices to analyze the model.
 Under my calibration, inventor productivity falls by about 2.5% over the
 period 1997-2012, consistent with the lower bounds of my estimates.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Column (4) in the upper panel of Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: RegProd"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 implies a lower bound for the fall in inventor productivity of about 1.5%,
 while the lower panel implies a fall in inventor productivity of at least
 4.8%.
 The 2.5% fall in my calibration is in between these two lower bounds.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This calibration therefore produces a lower bound for the impact of optimal
 R&D subsidies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: intPar"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 displays my choices for parameters calibrated externally.
 I set the discount rate to 
\begin_inset Formula $4\%$
\end_inset

, which, together with a 3% growth for my sample in 1997, implies a value
 for the real interest rate of 7%, in line with the long-run average before
 1997.
 I obtain a value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, the share of value added of each sector, from estimates of the Lerner
 Index in manufacturing that I obtain from the NBER-CES as described in
 Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:Using-the-Lerner"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 According to these estimates, about half of the sectors (weighted by sales)
 for which I have data saw an increase in the Lerner Index over the period.
 This suggests 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}=\beta_{2}=0.5.$
\end_inset

 Since I only have the Lerner Index for about half of the sectors, I rely
 on the extensive literature estimating markups to set a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=1.08$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, I follow 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "akcigitWhatHappenedBusiness2019a"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, who calibrate the same parameter using the midpoint of estimates provided
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "deloeckerRiseMarketPower2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "eggertssonKaldorPikettyFacts2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 As standard in the literature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "see e.g., "
key "acemogluIntellectualPropertyRights2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, I set the curvature of the incumbents' cost function relying on estimates
 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "kortumEquilibriumPatentRatio1993"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 I choose the lower bound of these estimates to minimize the asymmetry of
 innovation costs between incumbents and entrants, as more convex incumbents'
 costs mechanically make their research less effective than entrants.
 The rate of patent expiration comes directly from the legislative framework
 in the US, as established by the Uruguay Round Agreements Act of 1994.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 measures how radical are incumbents' innovations relative to entrants',
 I set 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0.785$
\end_inset

, the complement of the internal patent share of 21.5% estimated by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "akcigitGrowthHeterogeneousInnovations2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Turning to the value of blocking patents, parametrized by 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 in my model, I rely on estimates by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "czarnitzkiHowValuableAre2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "grimpePreemptingTechnologyCompetition2008"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, who employ merger data to obtain the effect of pre-emptive patents on
 the value of acquired firms.
 Both their estimates imply an elasticity of firm's values to the share
 of patents with pre-emptive value of more than one.
 This implies that a firm with a patent portfolio composed exclusively of
 defensive patents is valued on average twice as much as one with only patents
 that have no pre-emptive value.
 This suggest a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=2$
\end_inset

.
 As shown in the proof of Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:CGE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, my model gives an elasticity of firms' value of at most 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega-1$
\end_inset

, therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=2$
\end_inset

 effectively caps this elasticity to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 I also include R&D subsidies, modeled as a percent subsidy on inventors'
 wages,
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, and corporate taxes applied to firms instantaneous profits, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 I set these two parameters following the values reported by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "akcigitOptimalTaxationPolicies2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: intPar"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 describes my choices for the remaining parameters, which govern the scale
 of R&D and the growth rate in the economy.
 I set the incumbents' and entrants' R&D cost scale, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{I}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

, to match the share of inventors employed by incumbent firms in 1997 and
 the R&D business spending as a percent of GDP, as reported by the National
 Science Foundation.
 Intuitively, the two cost parameters jointly determine the overall R&D
 spending in the economy, while their relative value determines the distribution
 of R&D spending in equilibrium.
 Given the estimates for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{I}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

, I set 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 to match the growth in output per worker for the sectors considered in
 my analysis in 1997, 
\begin_inset Formula $3.03\%$
\end_inset

.
 All targets are matched almost exactly.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The average percentage point deviation of moments in the model from their
 empirical targets is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-6}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

