\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align left

\size small
Note: The figures reported in this table give the optimal allocation of
 R&D subsidies and the resulting aggregate outcomes for a planner wishing
 to maximize aggregate growth in the economy.
 The column headings refer to the various scenarios described above.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Baseline
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 refers to the subsidy allocation reflecting the 2012 equilibrium, where
 subsidies do not condition on sectors or the position of firms within sectors;
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Optimal Cost-Neutral
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 refer to the scenario where the planner is allowed to freely allocate R&D
 subsidies subject to the constraint that overall R&D subsidy expenditure
 as a percentage of GDP is held fixed at its 2012 benchmark; 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Cost-Neutral Sector
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 consider a scenario where the planner can choose which sector to allocate
 funds to, but not which firms within the sector should receive the subsidy;
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Cost-Neutral Entry
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 computes the optimal universal entry subsidy, under the assumption that
 the planner cannot condition its reception on the sector firms operate
 in.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


